<body class="font-sans bg-gray-100">

    <article class="max-w-6xl w-full mx-auto bg-white p-8 mt-6 shadow-lg rounded-lg">
        <span class="text-sm uppercase text-gray-600 tracking-wide">Article</span>

        <h1 id="blogTitle" class="text-4xl font-bold mt-2 text-gray-900 leading-tight"></h1>
        <div class="flex items-center text-sm text-gray-500 mt-2 space-x-6">
            <span class="flex items-center"><i class="far fa-user mr-2"></i> <span id="blogAuthor"></span></span>
            <span class="flex items-center"><i class="far fa-calendar mr-2"></i> <span id="blogDate"></span></span>
        </div>
        <img id="blogImage" class="mt-6 w-full h-96 object-cover rounded-lg shadow-md" alt="Blog Image">
        <p id="blogContent" class="mt-6 text-gray-700 text-lg leading-relaxed"></p>
        
        <p class="mt-6 text-gray-700 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            In a world dominated by fast fashion, making a conscious choice to embrace sustainability is more than a trendâ€”it's a movement towards a healthier planet and a more ethical industry. Sustainable fashion challenges us to think differently about the clothes we wear, focusing on their entire lifecycle from the materials they are made of to how they are produced and, eventually, disposed of. It's about choosing quality over quantity and timeless style over fleeting trends.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-gray-700 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            One of the most powerful ways to participate in this movement is by extending the life of our garments. This can be as simple as learning basic mending techniques to fix a loose button or a small tear, transforming a would-be discarded item into something wearable again. Upcycling takes this a step further, inviting creativity to turn old, worn-out pieces into entirely new creations, like turning a pair of old jeans into a stylish tote bag or a set of placemats.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-gray-700 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            Beyond our own closets, the second-hand market offers a treasure trove of unique, pre-loved items. Thrifting, consignment, and clothing swaps not only reduce textile waste but also give clothes a second chance at life. Every time we choose a second-hand garment, we are directly reducing the demand for new production, which in turn saves precious resources like water and energy and reduces carbon emissions. Embracing these practices allows us to build a unique wardrobe that reflects our personal style while aligning with our values for a better, more sustainable future.
        </p>
    </article>

    <section class="newsletter">
        <div class="container">
            <h2>Join Our Newsletter</h2>
            <p>Sign up for exclusive deals, new products, and promotions.</p>
            
            <form class="newsletter-form">
                <input type="email" placeholder="Enter your email" required>
                <button type="submit">Subscribe</button>
            </form>
        </div>
    </section>

    <script>
    // Fetch blog by ID from URL and render
    function getBlogIdFromUrl() {
        const match = window.location.pathname.match(/\/blog\/(\w+)/);
        return match ? match[1] : null;
    }
    function renderBlog(blog) {
        document.getElementById('blogTitle').textContent = blog.title;
        document.getElementById('blogAuthor').textContent = blog.author;
        document.getElementById('blogDate').textContent = new Date(blog.createdAt).toLocaleDateString();
        document.getElementById('blogImage').src = blog.image || '';
        document.getElementById('blogImage').alt = blog.title;
        document.getElementById('blogContent').textContent = blog.content;
    }
    function fetchBlog() {
        const blogId = getBlogIdFromUrl();
        if (!blogId) return;
        const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
        xhr.open('GET', `/api/v1/user/blogs/${blogId}`, true);
        xhr.onreadystatechange = function() {
            if (xhr.readyState === 4) {
                if (xhr.status === 200) {
                    const res = JSON.parse(xhr.responseText);
                    if (res.success && res.blog) {
                        renderBlog(res.blog);
                    } else {
                        document.body.innerHTML = '<div class="text-red-500 p-8">Blog not found.</div>';
                    }
                } else {
                    document.body.innerHTML = '<div class="text-red-500 p-8">Failed to load blog.</div>';
                }
            }
        };
        xhr.send();
    }
    fetchBlog();
    </script>
</body>